SOB 22: Write From Scratch a Small to Medium Sized Program for a Given Computing
Application


Hardware (Microcontroller)

Arduino Uno
LDR (Light Dependent Resistor) sensor
Ultrasonic distance sensor
Breadboard and jumper wires

Software

Arduino IDE
Python
PyCharm
PySerial library
Project Overview

This project implements a small Internet of Things (IoT) system using an
Arduino Uno and a Python application running on a computer.

Two sensors were connected to the microcontroller:

LDR Sensor – measures light intensity.
Ultrasonic Sensor – measures the distance of nearby objects.

The Arduino continuously reads data from both sensors and transmits the values
 to a Python program through serial communication. The Python script receives
 the data, stores it in variables, and displays the information on the console.

How the System Works

Arduino Side

The Arduino reads:

The LDR value using the analog input pin A0.
The distance measured by the ultrasonic sensor using the Trigger and Echo pins.

The readings are formatted as:
LDR_Value,Distance

Example:
345,12.6

The values are then sent to the computer through the serial connection every second.

Python Side

The Python script:

Opens the serial connection.
Reads incoming data from the Arduino.
Splits the incoming string using the comma separator.
Stores the values into variables:
ldr_value
distance
Prints the results to the console.

Example output:
LDR Value: 345
Distance: 12.6 cm
-------------------

Practical Demonstration

A video recording was produced showing the system operating correctly.

Ultrasonic Sensor Test

When a hand was placed in front of the ultrasonic sensor:

The measured distance decreased.
The Python console displayed smaller distance values.

Distance: 5.2 cm

This confirmed that the ultrasonic sensor was correctly detecting nearby objects.

LDR Sensor Test

When the LDR sensor was covered:

Less light reached the sensor.
The analog reading increased to values above approximately 300.

LDR Value: 320
LDR Value: 415

The updated values were immediately displayed on the Python console, confirming
 successful communication between the Arduino and Python application.

Reflection

This project demonstrates physical computing and basic IoT principles.
 The Arduino collects environmental data from an LDR sensor and an ultrasonic
  distance sensor, then transmits the information to a Python application through
   serial communication. The Python program successfully receives, processes,
    stores, and displays the sensor data in real time. Testing confirmed
     that covering the LDR increased the recorded light values and moving an
      object closer to the ultrasonic sensor reduced the measured distance.